<hl>
<seg id=1> The Inland Economic Development Will Provide Five Great Opportunities for Hong Kong SAR, Gu Yongjiang said. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Gu Yongjiang indicated that the inland economic development would provide five great opportunities for Hong Kong. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> - It is helpful for Hong Kong to have a long-term prosperous and steady economy. </seg>
<seg id=4> If inland economy grows steadily on a long-term basis, Hong Kong will benefit from the energetic inland economy. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=5> - It will provide more business opportunities for Hong Kong. </seg>
<seg id=6> Along with the scheduled opening of inland trade, finance, retail, and other services, Hong Kong's service industry will have a wider developing arena. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> - It is helpful for Hong Kong to strengthen its position of trade and navigation center. </seg>
<seg id=8> By year of 2010, the aggregate inland trade volume will hopefully hit 800 billion US dollars that no doubt will increase the need for transit and transhipment via Hong Kong. It will contribute Hong Kong to strengthen its position of trade and navigation center. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> - It will further stimulate the development of Hong Kong's finance market. </seg>
<seg id=10> Along with the deepening reform of state-owned enterprises, more share-holding enterprises will be listed on overseas stock market. Hong Kong will then be the first choice abroad for listed state-owned enterprises. </seg>
<seg id=11> This will expand the scale of Hong Kong's stock market, improve its structure, and stimulate the development of Hong Kong's bond market. More Chinese fund will emerge in Hong Kong. All those will consolidate and strengthen Hong Kong's position of international financial center. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> - It will improve the international competitive power of Hong Kong's commodity. </seg>
<seg id=13> The complementary economic relationship between inland and Hong Kong will combine the advantages of both places to enhance Hong Kong commodity's international competitive power. </seg>
</p>
